In the previous article, we implemented full user login and session management for our FastAPI blog. Now, the server can "remember" a user's login status and protect pages that require authentication.Since we can now distinguish between logged-in users and guests, it's the perfect time to add interactive features to our blog.In this article, we will add a fundamental yet crucial feature to our blog: a .Specifically, we will implement the following functionalities:Display a list of comments below each post.Allow logged-in users to post comments on articles.


  Step 1: Create the Data Model for Comments
Just like our  and  models, our  model needs its own data model and relationships with  and .


  1. Create the Comment Model
Open the  file, add the  model, and update the  and  models to establish a bi-directional relationship.Here, we've done three things: Created the  model, which includes , , and the foreign keys  and  that point to the  and  tables. Used  in the  model to define its "many-to-one" relationship with  and . Added the reverse "one-to-many" relationship  to the  and  models. This allows us to easily retrieve all comments for a  object or all comments made by a  object.Because we configured the  function in , it will automatically detect the  models and create or update the corresponding database tables when the application starts. We don't need to execute SQL manually.If you need to execute SQL manually, and your database is created on Leapcell,you can easily execute SQL statements through its graphical interface. Just go to the Database management page on the website, paste the above statements into the SQL interface, and execute them.


  Step 2: Implement the Business Logic for Comments
Next, we will create functions to handle comment creation and queries.Create a new file  in the project's root directory to store the business logic related to comments.The  function is used to fetch all comments under a post.  is used to save a new comment to the database. Because we have correctly set up the  in our models, we can later conveniently access the commenter's username in the template using .


  Step 3: Create Routes for Submitting and Displaying Comments
Now, we need to integrate the comment functionality into the post page. This requires two parts: a backend route to receive user-submitted comments, and an update to the post detail page route to display the comments.


  1. Create the Comment Route
Create a new file  in the  folder:This route only handles  requests. We use the  dependency we created earlier to protect it, ensuring only logged-in users can post comments. After a comment is successfully created, the page redirects back to the original post detail page.


  2. Update the Main Application and Post Routes
First, let's mount the comment router we just created in .Next, modify the  function in  so that when it renders the post detail page, it also fetches and passes all the comments for that post.


  Step 4: Update the Frontend View
The final step is to modify the template file to display the comment list and the comment form.Open , and add the following code below the post content and above the back link:{{ post.content | replace('\n', '') | safe }}Comments
    {% if comments %}
      {% for comment in comments %}
      {{ comment.content }}
          By {{ comment.user.username }} on {{ comment.createdAt.strftime('%Y-%m-%d') }}

      {% endfor %}
    {% else %}
      No comments yet. Be the first to comment!
    {% endif %}


  {% if user %}
  Leave a CommentSubmit Comment
  {% else %}
  Login to leave a comment.
  {% endif %}
 Back to Home
{% include "_footer.html" %}
We use {% for comment in comments %} to loop through and display all the comments. Through , we can directly show the commenter's username.We use  to check if the user is logged in. If they are, the comment form is displayed; otherwise, a login link is shown.To make the page look better, you can add some styles to :Now, restart your application:Open your browser and navigate to any post's detail page. You will see the new comments section.Type something into the comment box and submit it. After the page refreshes, you will see the comment you just posted in the comment list.Congratulations, you have successfully added a comment system to your blog!Of course, the current comment functionality is still quite basic. In the next article, we will continue to enhance this feature by implementing logic for authors to reply to comments, taking the blog's interactivity to the next level.

def cadastrar_livros(): print("-" * 85) nome_do_livro = input("Digite o nome do livro (ou 'sair' para encerrar): ") if nome_do_livro.lower() == "sair":autor = input("Digite o nome do autor: ") genero = input("Digite o gênero do livro: ") data_publicacao = input("Digite a data de publicação: ")
livro = { "nome_do_livro": nome_do_livro.title(), "autor": autor.title(), "genero": genero.title(), "data_publicacao": data_publicacao } return livro def mostrar_biblioteca(): print("\n Informações da biblioteca: ")for livro in biblioteca:
print(f"Nome do livro: {livro['nome_do_livro']}") print(f"Autor: {livro['autor']}") print(f"Gênero: {livro['genero']}") print(f"Data de publicação: {livro['data_publicacao']}") print("-" * 85) while True: livro = cadastrar_livros() break********** criei no google colab por insegurança de tentar sem ter ajuda da ia (infelizmente), mas fui utilizando a teoria que anotei das minhas aulas
